        <p>Hello, I’m Wilbur Suero</p>
        
        <p>
          I’m a <strong>Staff Backend Engineer</strong> specializing in <strong>Distributed Systems, Applied AI, and Ruby on Rails</strong>, based in La Romana, Dominican Republic. I design and scale SaaS products, build data-heavy distributed architectures, and engineer LLM-driven workflows that power conversational AI and analytics at scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          Currently, I work at <strong>Puzzle</strong>, where I own and ship production AI features supporting tens of thousands of daily users. I enjoy removing unnecessary complexity from software. Most engineering problems aren't solved by clever code—they're solved by choosing the right abstraction, understanding database indexes, and designing systems that operators can actually maintain without paging developers in the middle of the night.
        </p>
        
        <blockquote>
          “No Magic, Just Systems.”
        </blockquote>

        <h2 id="what-i-do">What I do</h2>
        <p>
          I care about building software that holds up under pressure. Not just software that works in a local sandbox or a quick demo, but systems that stay <strong>correct under concurrency</strong>, stay <strong>fast under high load</strong>, and remain <strong>predictable and debuggable</strong> when scaling up to millions of events.
        </p>
        <p>
          Most of my daily work centers around the intersection of <strong>applied AI and backend infrastructure</strong>: designing scalable pipelines for LLM-based classification, text extraction, and conversational analytics. I obsess over production constraints—optimizing background processing (Sidekiq, Redis, Elixir services) and reducing LLM API usage through batching strategies, early-exit flows, and atomic finalization workflows to maintain high trust and data consistency.
        </p>
        <p>
          My background includes a deep foundation in graphic design and multimedia, having graduated from the <strong>Altos de Chavón School of Design</strong> and <strong>ITLA</strong>. This unique design-leaning perspective gives me a high standard for usability, responsive interfaces, and developer experience—bridging the gap between robust system engineering and visual product execution.
        </p>

